    "type": "event",
    "content": {
      "title": "Apollo 11 — First Crewed Lunar Landing",
      "description": "At **20:17:40 UTC on July 20, 1969**, NASA astronauts **Neil Armstrong** and **Buzz Aldrin** landed the Lunar Module *Eagle* at **Tranquility Base** in the Sea of Tranquility — becoming the first humans ever to land on the Moon. Michael Collins remained in lunar orbit aboard Command Module *Columbia*.\n\nApproximately six hours after landing, Armstrong descended the ladder and spoke the iconic words: *\"That's one small step for [a] man, one giant leap for mankind.\"* Aldrin followed nineteen minutes later. The two spent roughly two and a half hours on the lunar surface, collecting 47.5 pounds (21.5 kg) of rock and soil samples, planting the American flag, and deploying scientific instruments.\n\nWatched live by an estimated **650 million viewers** worldwide, Apollo 11 fulfilled President Kennedy's 1961 challenge to land a man on the Moon before the decade's end. The crew splashed down safely in the Pacific Ocean on July 24, 1969.\n\nSee: [Wikipedia — Apollo 11](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollo_11) | [NASA Apollo 11 Mission Page](https://www.nasa.gov/mission/apollo-11/) | [Wikipedia — Tranquility Base](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tranquility_Base)",
      "description_format": "markdown",
      "date_label": "July 20, 1969 — 20:17 UTC",
      "tags": [
        "space",
        "nasa",
        "apollo-program",
        "moon",
        "neil-armstrong",
        "buzz-aldrin",
        "michael-collins",
